04824nam a2200673Ia 9781501717277DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20181986nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017172777 a10.7591/97815017172772doi  a(DE-B1597)503256  a(OCoLC)1038487350  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ1064.U6bF67 1985eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.2/6/09759631 aVesperi, Maria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCity of Green Benches :bGrowing Old in a New Downtown /cMaria Vesperi. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©1986  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Anthropology of Contemporary Issues00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAbout the Title of This Book -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE. The Apperception of Old Age -- t1. City of Green Benches -- t2. Reciprocity -- t3. Recognition -- tPART TWO. Social Policy and the Reality of Aging -- t4. Housing -- t5. Neighborly Senior Services -- t6. Mental Health Care -- tConclusion: Intelligere est pati -- tAfterword to the Cornell Paperbacks Edition -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSt. Petersburg, Florida, has become virtually synonymous with retirement and old age. The city of green benches once courted its elderly population; now, however, it seeks to rejuvenate its image, to attract the young through urban revitalization. In this humane and sensitive book, Maria Vesperi, an anthropologist and journalist, looks at the realities of being old and poor in the rapidly changing downtown of St. Petersburg. Vesperi provides a complete and carefully observed picture of the elderly: the conditions of their_ lives, representative social programs created to provide for them, and their interaction with the city around them. The life of the old in St. Petersburg, she notes, is characterized by a profound contradiction between how the elderly see themselves and how they are viewed by the community-a contradiction that speaks of the way cultural stereotypes about aging are transmitted to all older Americans. As a culture, Vesperi maintains, we view the old as an isolated segment of humanity without a living future or even an ongoing present. She seeks to understand the ways in which the old respond to the distorted image that they meet with every day, not only in their relations with individuals but in their dealings with the institutions set up specifically to care for them. Her study of St. Petersburg explores questions that are significant throughout the United States: How did our rigid cultural assumptions about old age develop, and how can we change them? Why do so many gerontologists, public officials, and social workers tacitly subscribe to that misconception? How does it inform the development and operation of public programs for the elderly? Enlivened by the voices of the old people of St. Petersburg and enriched with photographs by Ricardo Ferro, this moving book is important reading for anyone concerned with the life of the elderly in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aOlder peoplexServices forzFloridazSaint Petersburg. 0aOlder peoplezFloridazSaint Petersburg. 0aOlder people. 0aRetirementzFloridazSaint Petersburg. 4aAging. 4aAnthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171727740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717277423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501717277/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000